          "id": "at-l05-c1",
          "title": "CHAPTER 1 Nearest neighbors M y first brush with a computer",
          "content": "CHAPTER 1: Nearest Neighbors\nIn the mid-1970s, I had my first encounter with a computer program that was designed to provide companionship. At that time, I was a student at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT), where I had the opportunity to use a fascinating program called ELIZA. This program was unique because it imitated the way a therapist might converse with someone seeking support. When users typed in their thoughts or feelings, ELIZA would respond in a way that encouraged further reflection and conversation.\nFor instance, if a user typed, 'My mother is making me angry,' ELIZA might respond with questions like, 'Tell me more about your mother,' or 'What makes you feel that way about her?' These responses were not just random; they were designed to help users explore their feelings more deeply.\nIt's important to note that ELIZA did not truly understand emotions or relationships like a human would. It didn't have any real knowledge about what a mother is or what it means to feel angry. Instead, it used a clever technique of taking the words that users typed and transforming them into questions or rephrased statements. This way, ELIZA could create a dialogue that felt meaningful to the user, even though it was just a computer program.\nThis experience was significant for me because it highlighted how technology could facilitate conversations and provide a sense of companionship, even if it was through a simple program. It made me think about the ways in which we connect with others, and how technology might play a role in those connections. As we move forward in our exploration of technology and its impact on our lives, it's essential to consider both the benefits and limitations of these digital interactions. How do they shape our understanding of ourselves and our relationships with others? This chapter sets the stage for deeper discussions about the nature of companionship in an increasingly digital world.\nContext recap: CHAPTER 1: Nearest Neighbors\nIn the mid-1970s, I had my first encounter with a computer program that was designed to provide companionship. At that time, I was a student at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT), where I had the opportunity to use a fascinating program called ELIZA. This program was unique because it imitated the way a therapist might converse with someone seeking support. When users typed in their thoughts or feelings, ELIZA would respond in a way that encouraged further reflection and conversation.\nWhy this matters: CHAPTER 1 Nearest neighbors M y first brush with a computer helps learners in Technology/Psychology connect ideas from Alone Together to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
